  <main id="main"><header class="page-hero page-hero--diagonal"><div class="container"><div class="breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">Home</a> / <a href="fellowships.html">Fellowships</a> / Programs</div><span class="kicker">Fellowship programs</span><h1>Many disciplines. One standard of service.</h1><p>US Fellows appoints Humanity, Science, Civic, Education, Earth, Innovation, International Graduate, National Capacity, Senior, and Distinguished Fellows.</p></div></header><nav class="anchor-nav anchor-nav--bar" aria-label="On this page"><div class="container"><a href="#focus"><span>01</span>Areas of focus</a><a href="#overview"><span>02</span>Overview</a><a href="#principles"><span>03</span>Principles</a><a href="#process"><span>04</span>How it works</a><a href="#next"><span>05</span>Next steps</a></div></nav><section class="section focus-gallery" id="focus"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro section-intro--center"><span class="eyebrow">The fellowship pathway</span><h2>What this form of fellowship brings together</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Programs organize the Society by field and form of contribution while preserving a shared expectation of excellence, integrity, and service.</p></div><div class="focus-gallery__grid"><article class="dimension-card"><span>01</span><LegacyIcon name="compass" /><h3>Humanity, Civic, and Education</h3><p>Service involving dignity, public trust, community strength, learning, mentorship, and opportunity.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>02</span><LegacyIcon name="institution" /><h3>Science, Earth, and Innovation</h3><p>Research, discovery, stewardship, public-interest technology, and responsible solution-building.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>03</span><LegacyIcon name="lightbulb-o" /><h3>Graduate and National Capacity</h3><p>Field-aligned appointments and expertise applied to resilient institutions and critical public systems.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>04</span><LegacyIcon name="handshake-o" /><h3>Senior and Distinguished</h3><p>Experienced leaders whose contribution may include advising, convening, mentoring, and major missions.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section" id="overview"><div class="container editorial-grid"><div class="prose"><span class="eyebrow">The fellowship pathway</span><h2>Ten programs, one fellowship standard</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Programs organize the Society by field and form of contribution while preserving a shared expectation of excellence, integrity, and service.</p><p>A program name signals the mission context; the actual appointment is still shaped around the Fellow&#x27;s capabilities, the host&#x27;s need, and a defined public benefit.</p><p>Humanity, Civic, and Education establishes the point of entry; senior and distinguished defines what should remain after the immediate work is complete.</p></div><aside class="fact-panel"><h3>This page at a glance</h3><ul class="fact-list"><li><strong>Central question</strong>Ten programs, one fellowship standard</li><li><strong>Opening priorities</strong>Humanity, Civic, and Education; Science, Earth, and Innovation</li><li><strong>Extended scope</strong>Graduate and National Capacity; Senior and Distinguished</li></ul></aside></div></section><section class="section section--mist" id="principles"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Appointment standard</span><h2>Commitments behind a credible fellowship</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>A strong appointment aligns the Fellow, the institution, and the public value of the work.</p></div><div class="grid grid--3"><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">01</span><h3>Field alignment</h3><p>A Fellow&#x27;s knowledge and capabilities should be relevant to the work the appointment requires. In this context, consider humanity, civic, and education.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">02</span><h3>Institutional fit</h3><p>The host setting should make the contribution feasible, responsible, and useful. In this context, consider science, earth, and innovation.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">03</span><h3>Public value</h3><p>The appointment should create benefit beyond private career advancement or organizational convenience. In this context, consider graduate and national capacity.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section" id="process"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">From intent to practice</span><h2>From interest to appointment</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Appointments are shaped deliberately so that recognition, institutional affiliation, and useful work reinforce one another.</p></div><div class="steps"><article class="step"><h3>Express interest</h3><p>Describe your record, field, mission interests, and the contribution you are ready to make. Here, attend to humanity, civic, and education: Service involving dignity, public trust, community strength, learning, mentorship, and opportunity.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Establish fit</h3><p>Consider merit, readiness, mission alignment, and the setting in which the work can succeed. Here, attend to science, earth, and innovation: Research, discovery, stewardship, public-interest technology, and responsible solution-building.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Define the appointment</h3><p>Confirm scope, host support, responsibilities, intended benefit, and a practical working cadence. Here, attend to graduate and national capacity: Field-aligned appointments and expertise applied to resilient institutions and critical public systems.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Serve and reflect</h3><p>Complete the work with rigor, participate in Society life, and share transferable learning. Here, attend to senior and distinguished: Experienced leaders whose contribution may include advising, convening, mentoring, and major missions.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section layout-cta" id="next"><div class="container"><div class="cta"><div><h2>Move from interest toward appointment</h2><p>Begin with humanity, civic, and education, then define a contribution your capabilities or institution can support.</p></div><div class="actions"><a class="button button--gold" href="apply.html">Become a Fellow</a><a class="button button--outline" href="fellowship-programs.html">View programs</a></div></div><div class="atlas-links"><aside class="related-panel"><span class="eyebrow">Continue exploring</span><h3>Related pathways</h3><ul class="related-list"><li><a href="fellowship-programs.html">Fellowship programs</a></li><li><a href="selection-criteria.html">Selection criteria</a></li><li><a href="fellow-benefits.html">The Fellow experience</a></li></ul></aside></div></div></section></main>

